{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:25:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.16,0.03,0.16,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91214"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40318"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a sudden onset of central crushing chest pain that began while showering. He describes the pain as 7/10 intensity and has not experienced this type of pain previously. He has no significant medical history apart from hypercholesterolaemia and hypertension. His regular medications are perindopril. He is a lifelong non-smoker and consumes three to four standard drinks of alcohol per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 102/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 23/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals dual heart sounds with a pansystolic murmur best heard in the mid-axilla, and pitting oedema extending to mid-shins. Respiratory examination reveals no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal an ECG showing ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF with Q wave formation and reciprocal changes in aVL (Image). Cardiac biomarkers are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate method of calculating the 6-month mortality risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GRACE score","CHADS-VA score","CURB-65 score","Framingham Risk Score","TIMI Risk Score"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s ECG shows an inferior ST-elevation myocardial infarction, with ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF, Q wave formation, and reciprocal changes in aVL. This represents acute coronary syndrome requiring immediate management and risk stratification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGRACE score\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate tool for calculating 6-month mortality risk in patients with acute coronary syndrome. The Global Registry of Acute Coronary Events score incorporates age, heart rate, systolic blood pressure, serum creatinine, cardiac arrest on admission, raised cardiac biomarkers, ST segment changes, and Killip class to provide a percentage risk of 6-month mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETIMI Risk Score\u003C/strong\u003E is also used in acute coronary syndrome but estimates 30-day all-cause mortality rather than 6-month mortality. It incorporates seven criteria including age over 65, coronary risk factors, known stenosis, recent aspirin use, severe angina episodes, ST changes, and positive biomarkers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECHADS-VA score\u003C/strong\u003E is used to calculate stroke risk in patients with atrial fibrillation and includes congestive heart failure, hypertension, age, diabetes, stroke/transient ischaemic attack, and vascular disease. It is not relevant to acute coronary syndrome risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECURB-65 score\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess pneumonia severity and estimate mortality risk from community-acquired pneumonia. It incorporates confusion, urea, respiratory rate, blood pressure, and age over 65 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFramingham Risk Score\u003C/strong\u003E is used to calculate 10-year risk of developing coronary heart disease in asymptomatic individuals for primary prevention purposes. It is not appropriate for patients who already have acute coronary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The GRACE Risk and Mortality Calculator is used to estimate 6-month mortality for those with acute coronary syndrome.","The GRACE score incorporates factors such as age, heart rate, blood pressure, and cardiac biomarkers to assess risk.","The GRACE score is specifically designed for patients with acute coronary syndrome, including STEMI and NSTEMI."],"references":["Elbarouni B, Goodman SG, Yan RT, Welsh RC, Kornder JM, Deyoung JP, et al. Validation of the Global Registry of Acute Coronary Event (GRACE) risk score for in-hospital mortality in patients with acute coronary syndrome in Canada. Am Heart J [Internet]. 2009 [cited 2022 Jan 20];158(3):392\u20139. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19699862/","TIMI Risk Score for STEMI [Internet]. MDCalc. [cited 2022 Jan 20]. Available from: https://www.mdcalc.com/timi-risk-score-stemi","IMAGE; ECG; Buttner R, Burns E. Inferior STEMI [Internet]. Life in the Fast Lane \u2022 LITFL. 2018 [cited 2022 Jan 27]. Available from: https://litfl.com/inferior-stemi-ecg-library/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91214"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14378"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14378"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49b9238c-b778-4f9b-858a-e3725fb2a860.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49b9238c-b778-4f9b-858a-e3725fb2a860.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":413}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91214"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T19:41:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T20:07:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4134"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings